      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "perf(qmd): persistent export-state cache + stat fast path in exportSessions",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- **Problem:** For agents with thousands of session transcripts, `QmdMemoryManager.exportSessions()` was the dominant gateway CPU consumer. Every boot and every QMD sync interval walked every session JSONL and called `buildSessionEntry()` per file, which performs full read + parse + redaction + hash/render work even when the transcript export was unchanged.\n- **Why it matters:** The previous in-memory skip state only avoided some markdown rewrites after a manager instance had already rebuilt each entry. It did not survive gateway restart, so cold starts and periodic syncs could still create large CPU and GC spikes on production-sized transcript sets.\n- **What changed:**\n  1. Added a per-agent SQLite cache table, `qmd_session_export_cache`, in `openclaw-agent.sqlite`, keyed by `(session_file, export_dir, render_version)`.\n  2. Added a stat/fingerprint fast path before `buildSessionEntry()`. When cached `size`, `mtimeMs`, `ino`, and the edge content fingerprint match, and the cached markdown target still exists, QMD skips the expensive full-session rebuild.\n  3. Preserved the slow path for changed transcripts, missing markdown targets, mismatched cached targets, retention pruning, export-dir changes, and render-version changes.\n  4. Exposed QMD-specific host cache helpers through `openclaw/plugin-sdk/memory-core-host-engine-foundation`, keeping raw per-agent DB/Kysely access inside the core state owner.\n  5. Batch-loaded the current export scope cache rows once per `exportSessions()` pass and reused an in-memory lookup map, so large transcript sets do not reopen/refresh the per-agent DB accessor once per session file.\n\n**Scope boundary:** `renderSessionMarkdown()`, session redaction, line wrapping, and the markdown format QMD consumes are unchanged. `buildSessionEntry()` remains the authoritative slow path. The cache is scoped by export directory and `SESSION_EXPORT_RENDER_VERSION`, so config moves and render-byte changes invalidate cleanly.\n\n**Effect on Eddie's main agent (4,052 sessions / 158 MB):**\n- Boot QMD sync: **312s -> single-digit seconds**\n- Interval QMD sync: **38s -> ~50-500 ms**\n- The every-5-min CPU spike + GC tail collapses\n\n## Linked Issue\n\n- Closes openclaw-ys0 (Beads tracking issue)\n\n## Test Coverage\n\nNew and updated tests cover the cache contract:\n\n- `extensions/memory-core/src/memory/qmd-manager.test.ts`\n  - persists session-export state across manager restarts\n  - ignores cache rows scoped to a previous `exportDir`\n  - rebuilds markdown when the cached target has been deleted\n  - rebuilds the expected markdown when a current-scope cache row points at another target\n  - preserves existing session-export behavior for checkpoint/session filtering\n- `src/state/openclaw-agent-db.test.ts`\n  - schema shape includes the new table\n  - per-agent DB schema metadata and `user_version` now report version 2\n  - newer-schema refusal still protects downgrade safety\n\n## Tradeoffs / Known Caveats\n\n- The fast path intentionally uses stat identity plus a cheap first/last-byte fingerprint, not a full-file hash. That keeps the hot path cheap and catches common append/truncate/edge rewrites, but it is not meant to prove arbitrary middle-byte tampering with preserved size, mtime, and inode.\n- `SESSION_EXPORT_RENDER_VERSION` must be bumped when changing `renderSessionMarkdown()`, redaction, line wrapping, or any other logic that changes the bytes written to `qmd/sessions/*.md`.\n- No hand-written `CHANGELOG.md` entry is included; current repo policy keeps release notes out of normal PRs and derives them during release generation.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed:** QMD session export persists its unchanged-transcript fast-path state in the per-agent SQLite DB (the `qmd_session_export_cache` table) without exposing raw per-agent DB/Kysely access through the memory-core host SDK. It must still rebuild a markdown export when the cached target file has been deleted while the source JSONL and SQLite cache row remain unchanged, and current-scope cache rows must not suppress the expected export when their cached target points somewhere else.\n- **Real environment tested:** Current PR head `46ca88fbad` in the rebased `perf/qmd-export-stat-fast-path` worktree, using the real `QmdMemoryManager`, real `resolveMemoryBackendConfig`, the new QMD-specific host cache helpers, real per-agent `openclaw-agent.sqlite` storage, real `node:sqlite` reads of `qmd_session_export_cache`, and local `qmd 2.1.0` on PATH. The proof ran against an isolated `OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR` under `/tmp`; no Vitest harness or mocked QMD export cache was used.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** `node --import tsx --input-type=module` from the topic worktree with an inline driver. The driver created one session JSONL, ran `QmdMemoryManager.sync({ reason: \"manual\" })` across three manager instances, inspected `qmd_session_export_cache`, deleted the generated markdown target, and verified the next sync rebuilt it.\n- **Evidence after fix:** Captured terminal output from the live run:\n\n```text\n=== Phase 1: first boot writes markdown and SQLite cache ===\n[memory] qmd watcher starting for agent \"main\" paths=2\n[memory] qmd manager initialized for agent \"main\" mode=full collections=3 durationMs=1603\n[memory] qmd watcher ready for agent \"main\" paths=2 durationMs=27\n[memory] qmd sync completed for agent \"main\" reason=boot durationMs=381\nboot 1: sync done in 383 ms\nexport exists: true\nexport contains proof text: true\nsqlite cache rows: 1; renderVersion=1; fingerprintLen=40\ncache target is export file: true\nexport mtimeMs: 1781377796882.765\n\n=== Phase 2: second boot unchanged input uses fast path ===\n[memory] qmd watcher starting for agent \"main\" paths=2\n[memory] qmd manager initialized for agent \"main\" mode=full collections=3 durationMs=1073\n[memory] qmd watcher ready for agent \"main\" paths=2 durationMs=5\n[memory] qmd sync completed for agent \"main\" reason=boot durationMs=323\nboot 2: sync done in 326 ms\nexport mtime unchanged: true\nexport size unchanged: true\n\n=== Phase 3: delete markdown while SQLite cache survives ===\nexport exists after delete: false\nsqlite cache rows still present: 1\n=== Phase 4: third boot rebuilds missing target ===\n[memory] qmd watcher starting for agent \"main\" paths=2\n[memory] qmd manager initialized for agent \"main\" mode=full collections=3 durationMs=1104\n[memory] qmd watcher ready for agent \"main\" paths=2 durationMs=5\n[memory] qmd sync completed for agent \"main\" reason=boot durationMs=329\nboot 3: sync done in 331 ms\nrebuilt export exists: true\nrebuilt contains proof text: true\nrebuilt mtime newer than first: true\nsqlite cache rows after rebuild: 1\n\nAll runtime assertions passed.\n```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** The first sync wrote the markdown export and one SQLite cache row with `renderVersion=1`, a 40-character content fingerprint, and the expected markdown target. The second sync preserved the markdown mtime and size, proving unchanged input took the fast path without rewriting the export. After deleting the markdown while leaving the SQLite cache row intact, the third sync rebuilt the target with the expected content and a newer mtime, proving the missing-target path falls through to the slow rebuild rather than trusting stale cache state. Separately, the focused regression test now seeds a current-scope cache row whose stat/fingerprint still match but whose target points outside the export dir, deletes the expected export, and verifies the next sync rebuilds the expected markdown and rewrites the cache target back to the derived in-root path. The current implementation also loads current-scope cache rows once before the session loop and reuses a `Map` lookup for all session files, removing the per-session cache-accessor refresh that Clawsweeper flagged.\n- **What was not tested:** I did not rerun a benchmark against Eddie's full 4,052-session production corpus after the SDK-boundary rewrite, rebase, cached-target validation fix, and batch-read follow-up. The proof above validates the current SQLite cache behavior and missing-target regression path on real runtime code; the original production-sized timing numbers remain observational context.\n\n## Verification\n\nCurrent head includes follow-up commits `de868a0588` (`fix(qmd): narrow export-cache host seam`), `c7d21ff777` (`chore(qmd): drop release-owned changelog edit`), `7adc84d69a` (`fix(qmd): validate cached export targets`), and `46ca88fbad` (`fix(qmd): batch export-cache reads`) after rebasing onto current `origin/main`. Commands run after the current patch:\n\n```text\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-core/src/memory/qmd-manager.test.ts -t \"session-export|previous exportDir|cached target|current-scope cache row\"\n# 4 passed, 127 skipped\n\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-core/src/memory/qmd-manager.test.ts\n# 131 passed\n\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/state/openclaw-agent-db.test.ts\n# 11 passed\n\npnpm tsgo:core\n# exited 0\n\npnpm tsgo:core:test\n# exited 0\n\npnpm plugin-sdk:api:check\n# OK docs/.generated/plugin-sdk-api-baseline.sha256\n\npnpm config:schema:check\n# [base-config-schema] ok\n\npnpm oxlint extensions/memory-core/src/memory/qmd-manager.ts extensions/memory-core/src/memory/qmd-manager.test.ts src/plugin-sdk/memory-core-host-engine-foundation.ts src/state/openclaw-agent-db.ts\n# clean\n\ngit diff --check\n# clean\n\nnode --import tsx --input-type=module\n# real-runtime QMD/SQLite proof above; All runtime assertions passed.\n```\n\n",
        "branch": "perf/qmd-export-stat-fast-path",
